<subSubSection pageId="89" pageNumber="90" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="89.[151,1437,941,1903]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1229,1255]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Remarks</emphasis>
. This is a widely distributed Palaearctic species and is not uncommon in 
<collectingRegion box="[1125,1238,1229,1255]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1249,1313,1229,1255]" name="Japan" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Japan</collectingCountry>
(633 Japanese specimens recorded by National Museum of Nature and Science 2021), but it seems rare in the Russian Far East and 
<collectingCountry box="[252,324,1301,1327]" name="South Korea" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Korea</collectingCountry>
. In 
<collectingCountry box="[362,433,1301,1327]" name="South Korea" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Korea</collectingCountry>
, only one old female specimen labelled “Tonai [=Tonae, 
<collectingRegion box="[1063,1230,1301,1327]" country="North Korea" name="Yanggang-do" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Ryanggang-do</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1239,1385,1301,1327]" name="North Korea" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">North Korea</collectingCountry>
], 
<date pageId="89" pageNumber="90" value="1935-07-23">23. VII. 1935</date>
, K. Takeuchi”, has been recorded (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[660,856,1337,1363]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
) and we have not seen any specimens or published collection records from 
<collectingCountry box="[419,564,1373,1399]" name="South Korea" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">South Korea</collectingCountry>
. Lee 
<emphasis box="[623,679,1373,1399]" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">et al.</emphasis>
’s (2019) record of “ 
<collectingCountry box="[905,976,1373,1399]" name="South Korea" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Korea</collectingCountry>
(South)” needs confirmation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="89.[151,1437,941,1903]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
In our COI analysis (
<figureCitation box="[434,531,1409,1436]" captionStart="FIGURE 151" captionStartId="238.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[163,1422,186,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-26@238.[157,1430,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="238" captionText="FIGURE 151. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 4." pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 151</figureCitation>
), the only specimen available from Primorskij Kraj formed a clade with northern European specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[455,541,1445,1471]" name="Finland" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Finland</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[598,688,1445,1471]" name="Norway" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Norway</collectingCountry>
with 100% UFBoot support and this clade was retrieved as sister to a clade of Japanese specimens with 98% UFBoot support; then, this clade of northern European and East Asian specimens was part of the polytomous clade with 100% UFBoot support mostly containing central European material from 
<collectingCountry box="[281,385,1553,1579]" name="Germany" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Germany</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[444,581,1553,1579]" name="Switzerland" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
. For the NaK analysis, only one Norwegian and three Japanese specimens were available and they formed a clade with 100% UFBoot support (
<figureCitation box="[929,1027,1589,1615]" captionStart="FIGURE 161" captionStartId="246.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[177,1403,189,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@246.[171,1417,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="246" captionText="FIGURE 161. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 2." pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 161</figureCitation>
). It is interesting that the East Asian specimens are genetically closer to the northern European specimens than to the central European specimens. This may have some connection with 
<bibRefCitation author="Benson, R. B." box="[516,699,1661,1688]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" pagination="25 - 33" refId="ref72962" refString="Benson, R. B. (1945) Classification of the Pamphiliidae (Hymenoptera Symphyta). Proceedings of the Royal Entomological Society of London, Series B, Taxonomy, 14 (3 - 4), 25 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1945. tb 00012. x" type="journal article" year="1945">Benson’s (1945)</bibRefCitation>
finding of pale (south) and dark (north) color forms in Britain and establishment of a new subspecies, 
<taxonomicName authority="Benson, 1945" authorityName="Benson" authorityYear="1945" box="[554,963,1697,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Anoplolyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="hortorum" subSpecies="bicinctus">
<emphasis box="[554,797,1697,1723]" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">P. hortorum bicinctus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Benson, R. B." box="[805,963,1697,1724]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" pagination="25 - 33" refId="ref72962" refString="Benson, R. B. (1945) Classification of the Pamphiliidae (Hymenoptera Symphyta). Proceedings of the Royal Entomological Society of London, Series B, Taxonomy, 14 (3 - 4), 25 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1945. tb 00012. x" type="journal article" year="1945">Benson, 1945</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, for the northern dark form, which occurs also in 
<collectingCountry box="[234,326,1733,1759]" name="Sweden" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Sweden</collectingCountry>
. The specimens from Primorskij Kraj (
<figureCitation box="[767,849,1733,1759]" captionStart="FIGURE 83" captionStartId="172.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-26@172.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="172" captionText="FIGURE 83. Pamphilius hortorum, female, Russia – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) sawsheath laterally, (h) claw." pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 83</figureCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry box="[914,978,1733,1759]" name="Japan" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[994,1076,1733,1759]" captionStart="FIGURE 84" captionStartId="173.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-19@173.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="173" captionText="FIGURE 84. Pamphilius hortorum, female, Japan – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) sawsheath laterally, (h) claw." pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
) are darker than the central European specimens and may agree with the diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benson" authorityYear="1945" box="[768,1009,1769,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Anoplolyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="hortorum" subSpecies="bicinctus">
<emphasis box="[768,1009,1769,1795]" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">P. hortorum bicinctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We are not advocating the validity of Benson’s subspecies, but the occurrence of morphologically and genetically similar populations in northern Europe and the Far East should be investigated with much more material from throughout the distribution range of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
